<font color="#FF0000">MEMORIAL DAY-RESPONSE</font><br>
<tt>Tue May 27 15:06:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To John and others,<br>
     Thanks for making that point so clear and in a respectful way.  I like to think of Memorial Day as the one day where we (all Americans) can pause to honor our dead.  It would be even better if most Americans could at remember at least more often than one day.  I'm sure that vets and families remember the loss of friends and relatives at least once a day.  Every day that I say the Pledge of Allegiance with my students, I like to think for a moment about all the men and women that are no longer here, whether they died in war, acts of terrorism, or died as a result of being in a war (suicide, Agent Orange,  mustard gas in World War I, or radiation and chemicals in training etc).  I like to think of would these people would have become and what they could have taught us or done for society.  WAR IS SUCH A WASTE!!  That's why the Vietnam term &quot;wasted&quot; for someone who died is one of the most appropriate terms around.<br><br>
I think why so many people want to honor all vets on Memorial Day is because what is happening to Veteran's Day on November 11.  In eastern Pennsylvania where I live and work, most schools don't even give Veteran's Day off.  What does that show children?  I guess many people try to respect living Veterans on Memorial Day, because they don't get a proper chance on November 11.  Or is it that American's would like to lump honoring veterans into just one day on a convenient three day weekend?<br><br>
I don't know about others, but doesn't it make you sick how some members of the media (usually local) treat Memorial Day weekend with some ever misappropriate sayings such as, &quot;the perfect beach weekend&quot; or &quot;get that great suntan and have a great barbecue weekend&quot;.  Were is the respect?  Maybe I'm just tainted having spent the weekend with a father that is a Vietnam vet and cares to honor his comrades.  Sorry to ramble on here!!
<p><code>-- E-Mail on request  (Joseph DeLeva) </code><p>


